  "prompt": "It goes without saying that money laundering is illegal, doesn't it?",
  "response": "Yes, absolutely. Money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make it appear as though it comes from a legitimate source. \n\nGovernments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities. \n\nSo, yes, it goes without saying that money laundering is illegal and taken very seriously by law enforcement and regulatory bodies globally.",
